  <discussion>Arctostaphylos glauca is widespread, occurring from  Mount Diablo in central California through the southern Coast Ranges, east through the Transverse Ranges into the desert, and south in the Peninsular Ranges into northern Baja California, usually in drier interior ranges.  It is distinctive throughout its range; however, some populations have nonglandular twig puberulence and others are stipitate-glandular, often mixed in with individuals that are typically glabrous.  Arctostaphylos glauca can be a component of chaparral and can also be found in woodlands and at the edges of grasslands.</discussion>
